# Internationalization (i18n) - MANDATORY

*ALWAYS use translation keys for all user-facing text. NEVER hardcode text strings.*

## Rules:
1. All visible text in components must use translation keys from the i18n system
2. Translation files are located in src/i18n/lng/ (en.json, he.json)
3. Use the existing page keys from src/constants/stringsRes/translationPageKeys.ts when applicable
4. When adding new text:
   - First add the translation key to BOTH en.json and he.json
   - Then reference it using the translation hook/function (e.g., t('page.key'))

## ❌ Bad (hardcoded text):
tsx
<h1>Welcome to our platform</h1>
<button>Submit</button>
<p>Enter your email address</p>


## ✅ Good (using translation keys):
tsx
<h1>{t('home_page.welcome_title')}</h1>
<button>{t('common.submit_button')}</button>
<p>{t('form.email_placeholder')}</p>


## Exceptions:
- Technical identifiers (CSS classes, IDs, data attributes)
- Code comments
- Console logs for debugging
- Constants that are not user-facing (API endpoints, config values)

## When creating new pages or components:
1. Create a new section in the translation files if needed
2. Add the page key to translationPageKeys.ts if it's a new page
3. Use descriptive, hierarchical keys (e.g., page_name.section.element)---
